    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "09c6a083_24838c4c",
        "filename": "util/process/process_id.h",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 41,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-04-22T21:16:49Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I’m assuming that for the POSIX case, we can assume (perhaps checked via static_cast) that pid_t is a particular underlying type (int) and not have to cast to int_max_t or use PRIdMAX.",
      "revId": "3a61ec177db753a96afcee7d609958ca07648451",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "72946962_19b7f5a2",
        "filename": "util/process/process_id.h",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 41,
      "author": {
        "id": 1317891
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-04-23T15:17:34Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Actually, not according to the POSIX standard. The strict POSIX standard only specifies that pid_t is a signed integer, and explicitly does not specify its size or underlying type.\n\nThe GNU C library, on the other hand, explicitly states that pid_t is an int. (https://www.gnu.org/software/libc/manual/html_node/Process-Identification.html)\n\nI went with standards compliance, figuring taking this as broadly as possible was a good idea. Which should we go with here: cleanliness, or strict standards compliance?",
      "parentUuid": "09c6a083_24838c4c",
      "revId": "3a61ec177db753a96afcee7d609958ca07648451",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "62469090_b372ad8c",
        "filename": "util/process/process_id.h",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 41,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-04-23T15:43:21Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is not what I had in mind when I said \"POSIX case.\" I meant _our_ POSIX platforms, not _all_ POSIX platforms.\n\nCrashpad is necessarily very platform-specific, there can never be a true generic \"POSIX port\" of so much of this code that it\u0027s not valuable to attempt just for its own sake. We know that pid_t is int on _our_ POSIX platforms and can use that knowledge to simplify here. You are correct about it not being truly conformant, which is why I suggested a static_assert to guarantee equivalence. If we ever do need to support a POSIX platform where pid_t is, say, long, this assertion (like so many others) would alert us and we could easily accommodate it in this #if cascade.",
      "parentUuid": "72946962_19b7f5a2",
      "revId": "3a61ec177db753a96afcee7d609958ca07648451",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    }
